1 Client Bio ð¥

1.1 Client

Olivia Newton-John Cancer Research Institute (ONJCRI)

1.2 Bio

ONJCRI is committed to discovering and developing innovative cancer therapies. By integrating scientific research with clinical practice, the institute transforms laboratory findings into clinical trials to improve patient outcomes and quality of life for people affected by cancer across Australia (ONJCRI, 2025).

2 Recommendation ð

Given the moderate positive correlation between lymph node ratio (LNR) and breast cancer (BC) mortalityâand its role as an independent prognostic factorâit is recommended that ONJCRI further investigate the spatial distribution of regional lymph node metastases, which may support more informed clinical decision-making (Savas et al., 2023).

3.1 Initial Data Analysis (IDA)

data <- read.csv("breast_cancer.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

library(survival)
library(survminer)
library(car)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

library(plyr)

str(data)
names(data)

data$Status <- ifelse(data$Status =='Alive',0,1)
data$Grade <- factor(data$Grade, 
                     levels = c(1, 2, 3, "anaplastic; Grade IV"), 
                     labels = c("I", "II", "III", "IV"))
data <- data %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), factor))
data$Lymph.Node.Ratio <- data$Reginol.Node.Positive/data$Regional.Node.Examined
data$Tumor.Size.Group <- cut(data$Tumor.Size, 
                             breaks = c(0, 20, 50, 100, Inf), 
                             labels = c("â¤20mm", "21-50mm", "51-100mm", ">100mm"))

sum(is.na(data))

3.1.1 Overview

The dataset used in this study was sourced from IEEE DataPort and comprises 4,024 samples with 16 variables detailing population-based breast cancer (BC) statistics from 2006 to 2010.

Key variables analysed include:

  • Survival Months
  • Survival Status
  • Lymph Node Ratio (LNR)

3.1.2 Assumptions

Assumptions made include:

  • Observations are assumed to be independent.
  • Assumes a significance level of Î± = 0.05.
  • The hazard ratio between groups is assumed to be constant over time.
  • The relationship between covariates and the log hazard is assumed to be linear.
  • Censoring is assumed to be non-informative (independent of survival time).
  • Systematic and random errors in clinical assessment are minimal, with limited impact on the data.
  • The sample is representative of the broader breast cancer (BC) population.

3.1.3 Data Cleaning

The dataset was prepared as followed:

  • The Lymph Node Ratio (LNR) was computed as the number of positive nodes divided by the total number of examined regional nodes.
  • Character fields such as Grade were factorised for analysis; Status was binary encoded as 0 (Alive) and 1 (Dead).

3.2 Survival Analysis

To address the lack of a granular lymphatic staging framework in the dataset, LNR was used as a proxy indicator, as previously validated by Sakin and Aldemir (2020).

load("data.Rdata")

p <- ggplot(data, aes(x = Lymph.Node.Ratio)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, fill = "#FFFAF0", color = "black", alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = "Lymph Node Ratio Distribution", x = "Lymph Node Ratio(%)", y = "Frequency") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16, face = "bold"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size = 14),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size = 14),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.position = "none"
  )

cox_model_full <- coxph(Surv(Survival.Months, Status) ~ ., 
                        data = data)

final_model <- step(cox_model_full, direction = 'backward')

ph_test <- cox.zph(final_model)
print("Proportional Hazards Assumption Test Results")
print(ph_test)
print(paste("Global test p-value for proportional hazards assumption", ph_test$table["GLOBAL", "p"]))

final_model <- coxph(Surv(Survival.Months, Status) ~ Age + Race + T.Stage + N.Stage + 
                     Differentiate + Regional.Node.Examined + Reginol.Node.Positive + 
                     Lymph.Node.Ratio, data = data)

ph_test <- cox.zph(final_model)
print("Final Model Proportional Hazards Assumption Test Results")
print(ph_test)

png("schoenfeld_residuals.png", width = 1800, height = 1500, res = 150)

variables <- rownames(ph_test$table)
variables <- variables[variables != "GLOBAL"]
n_plots <- length(variables)
n_cols <- 2
n_rows <- ceiling(n_plots / n_cols)

par(mfrow = c(n_rows, n_cols), 
    mar = c(5, 5, 4, 2) + 0.1, 
    oma = c(0, 2, 5, 0))

for(i in 1:length(variables)) {
  plot(ph_test, var = i, main = "")
  title(main = variables[i], line = 1)
}

title(main = "Schoenfeld Residuals for Cox Proportional Hazards Model", 
      outer = TRUE, cex.main = 1.5, line = 3)

mtext(paste("Global Test p-value:", round(ph_test$table["GLOBAL", "p"], 4)), 
      side = 3, outer = TRUE, line = 1, cex = 1.1)

dev.off()

cat("Schoenfeld residual plots saved as 'schoenfeld_residuals.png'\n")

summary(final_model)

phtb <- print(ph_test)

phtb <- phtb[phtb[,3]>0.05,];Variable.name <- rownames(phtb);Variable.name <- Variable.name[-length(Variable.name)]
data <- data[,c('Survival.Months','Status',Variable.name)]

cox_model_final <- coxph(Surv(Survival.Months, Status) ~ ., 
                         data = data)

model_summary <- summary(cox_model_final)

print("Summary of the Cox Proportional Hazards Model")
print(model_summary)

Based on the results of Chi-square testing, Cox regression analyses (both univariate and multivariate), and stepwise feature selectionâalong with verification of the proportional hazards assumption (global PH test: p = 0.76)âthe hazard function was specified as follows:

\begin{aligned} h(t) &= h_0(t) \times \exp(\beta_1 X_1 + \beta_2 X_2 + \ldots + \beta_p X_p) \\ &= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(0.019617 \times \text{Age} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} - 0.857562 \times \text{Race\_Other} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} - 0.488841 \times \text{Race\_White} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} + 0.376052 \times \text{T Stage\_T2} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} + 0.489402 \times \text{T Stage\_T3} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} + 0.843881 \times \text{T Stage\_T4} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} + 0.393576 \times \text{N Stage\_N2} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} + 0.532131 \times \text{N Stage\_N3} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} + 0.521606 \times \text{Poorly differentiated} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} + 1.214208 \times \text{Undifferentiated} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} - 0.478967 \times \text{Well differentiated} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} - 0.018073 \times \text{Regional Node Examined} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} + 0.041170 \times \text{Regional Node Positive} \\ &\phantom{= h_0(t) \times \exp\big(} + 0.556376 \times \text{Lymph Node Ratio}\big) \end{aligned}

  • Harrellâs C-index: 0.72 (SE = 0.011)
  • Log-rank test: p < 2 Ã 10-16

Notably, LNR showed a moderately positive correlation with BC mortality risk, with a regression coefficient of 0.55âeach unit increase raises the log hazard by 0.55, controlling for other variables.

This association was corroborated by the forest plot, which demonstrated a statistically significant relationship between LNR and increased BC mortality (HR = 1.775, 95% CI: 1.02â2.99, p = 0.042), indicating a 77.5% higher hazard per unit increase, holding all other covariates constant.

To further evaluate prognostic differences, patient cases were stratified into high- and low-risk groups based on the median LNR of 0.214. The KaplanâMeier curve was then plotted to compare the survival probabilities between the two groups.

Show the code 
median_lpl <- median(data$Lymph.Node.Ratio)
data$Lymph.Node.Ratio.group <- ifelse(data$Lymph.Node.Ratio > median_lpl, 
                                            'highLym', 'lowLym')
km_Lym <- survfit(Surv(Survival.Months, Status) ~ Lymph.Node.Ratio.group, 
                 data = data)
print("Kaplan-Meier Survival Analysis Results")
print(km_Lym)
survdiff_Lym <- survdiff(Surv(Survival.Months, Status) ~ Lymph.Node.Ratio.group, 
                        data = data)
print("Log-rank Test Result for Lymph Node Ratio Grouping")
print(survdiff_Lym)

consistent_font_size <- 16

  data = data, 
  pval = TRUE,
  conf.int = TRUE,

Stratification revealed a significantly higher survival probability in patients with lower LNR (p < 2 Ã 10-16), supporting its use as a meaningful risk grouping strategy. This is consistent with studies reporting that LNR outperforms conventional nodal staging in predicting outcomes and guiding postmastectomy radiotherapy (Jin et al., 2021).

3.3 Limitations

  • The Status variable over-represents living individuals, potentially skewing the results.
  • The dataset, collected from 2006â2010, may not reflect current clinical practices, limiting the reportâs applicability.
  • Absence of data on lymph node location constrains clinical interpretation.

Potential improvements include using recent cohort data and incorporating anatomical mapping of lymph node involvement, as recommended to enable spatial analysis of regional metastases.

```{r}
load("data.Rdata")

Variable.name <- c("Age" ,"Race" ,"Marital.Status","T.Stage","N.Stage","X6th.Stage","Differentiate","Grade","A.Stage","Tumor.Size","Estrogen.Status","Progesterone.Status","Regional.Node.Examined","Reginol.Node.Positive","Lymph.Node.Ratio","Tumor.Size.Group")
res=ezcox(data = data,covariates = Variable.name,time = 'Survival.Months',status = 'Status',model_dir = getwd())

knitr::kable(res) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"),
                full_width = FALSE,
                font_size = 12) %>%
  scroll_box(width = "100%", height = "400px")
```

```{r}
#| warning: false
#| results: "hide"
load("data.Rdata")

p <- ggplot(data, aes(x = Lymph.Node.Ratio)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.05, fill = "#FFFAF0", color = "black", alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = "Lymph Node Ratio Distribution", x = "Lymph Node Ratio(%)", y = "Frequency") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16, face = "bold"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size = 14),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size = 14),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.position = "none"
  )

cox_model_full <- coxph(Surv(Survival.Months, Status) ~ ., 
                        data = data)

final_model <- step(cox_model_full, direction = 'backward')

ph_test <- cox.zph(final_model)
print("Proportional Hazards Assumption Test Results")
print(ph_test)
print(paste("Global test p-value for proportional hazards assumption", ph_test$table["GLOBAL", "p"]))

final_model <- coxph(Surv(Survival.Months, Status) ~ Age + Race + T.Stage + N.Stage + 
                     Differentiate + Regional.Node.Examined + Reginol.Node.Positive + 
                     Lymph.Node.Ratio, data = data)

ph_test <- cox.zph(final_model)
print("Final Model Proportional Hazards Assumption Test Results")
print(ph_test)

png("schoenfeld_residuals.png", width = 1800, height = 1500, res = 150)

variables <- rownames(ph_test$table)
variables <- variables[variables != "GLOBAL"]
n_plots <- length(variables)
n_cols <- 2
n_rows <- ceiling(n_plots / n_cols)

par(mfrow = c(n_rows, n_cols), 
    mar = c(5, 5, 4, 2) + 0.1, 
    oma = c(0, 2, 5, 0))

for(i in 1:length(variables)) {
  plot(ph_test, var = i, main = "")
  title(main = variables[i], line = 1)
}

title(main = "Schoenfeld Residuals for Cox Proportional Hazards Model", 
      outer = TRUE, cex.main = 1.5, line = 3)

mtext(paste("Global Test p-value:", round(ph_test$table["GLOBAL", "p"], 4)), 
      side = 3, outer = TRUE, line = 1, cex = 1.1)

dev.off()

cat("Schoenfeld residual plots saved as 'schoenfeld_residuals.png'\n")

summary(final_model)

phtb <- print(ph_test)

phtb <- phtb[phtb[,3]>0.05,];Variable.name <- rownames(phtb);Variable.name <- Variable.name[-length(Variable.name)]
data <- data[,c('Survival.Months','Status',Variable.name)]

cox_model_final <- coxph(Surv(Survival.Months, Status) ~ ., 
                         data = data)

model_summary <- summary(cox_model_final)

print("Summary of the Cox Proportional Hazards Model")
print(model_summary)
```

```{r}
#| echo: false
knitr::asis_output("Based on the results of Chi-square testing, Cox regression analyses (both univariate and multivariate), and stepwise feature selectionâalong with verification of the proportional hazards assumption (global PH test: p = 0.76)âthe hazard function was specified as follows:

$$
\\begin{aligned}
h(t) &= h_0(t) \\times \\exp(\\beta_1 X_1 + \\beta_2 X_2 + \\ldots + \\beta_p X_p) \\\\
&= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(0.019617 \\times \\text{Age} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} - 0.857562 \\times \\text{Race\\_Other} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} - 0.488841 \\times \\text{Race\\_White} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} + 0.376052 \\times \\text{T Stage\\_T2} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} + 0.489402 \\times \\text{T Stage\\_T3} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} + 0.843881 \\times \\text{T Stage\\_T4} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} + 0.393576 \\times \\text{N Stage\\_N2} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} + 0.532131 \\times \\text{N Stage\\_N3} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} + 0.521606 \\times \\text{Poorly differentiated} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} + 1.214208 \\times \\text{Undifferentiated} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} - 0.478967 \\times \\text{Well differentiated} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} - 0.018073 \\times \\text{Regional Node Examined} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} + 0.041170 \\times \\text{Regional Node Positive} \\\\
&\\phantom{= h_0(t) \\times \\exp\\big(} + 0.556376 \\times \\text{Lymph Node Ratio}\\big)
\\end{aligned}
$$

* Harrell's C-index: 0.72 (SE = 0.011)
* Log-rank test: *p* < 2 Ã 10<sup>-16</sup>

Notably, LNR showed a moderately positive correlation with BC mortality risk, with a regression coefficient of 0.55âeach unit increase raises the log hazard by 0.55, controlling for other variables.

This association was corroborated by the forest plot, which demonstrated a statistically significant relationship between LNR and increased BC mortality (HR = 1.775, 95% CI: 1.02â2.99, *p* = 0.042), indicating a 77.5% higher hazard per unit increase, holding all other covariates constant.")
```

```{r}
#| fig.width: 14
#| fig.height: 12
#| results: "hide"
median_lpl <- median(data$Lymph.Node.Ratio)
data$Lymph.Node.Ratio.group <- ifelse(data$Lymph.Node.Ratio > median_lpl, 
                                            'highLym', 'lowLym')
km_Lym <- survfit(Surv(Survival.Months, Status) ~ Lymph.Node.Ratio.group, 
                 data = data)
print("Kaplan-Meier Survival Analysis Results")
print(km_Lym)
survdiff_Lym <- survdiff(Surv(Survival.Months, Status) ~ Lymph.Node.Ratio.group, 
                        data = data)
print("Log-rank Test Result for Lymph Node Ratio Grouping")
print(survdiff_Lym)

consistent_font_size <- 16  

p <- ggsurvplot(
  km_Lym, 
  data = data, 
  pval = TRUE,
  conf.int = TRUE,
  risk.table = TRUE,
  risk.table.col = "strata",
  legend.title = "Lymph.Node.Ratio Group",
  xlab = "Time in months",
  ylab = "Survival probability",
  palette = c("#911eb4", "#f58231"),
  legend.labs = c("highLym", "lowLym"),
  tables.theme = theme_cleantable() + 
                 theme(
                   axis.title.x = element_text(size = consistent_font_size, family = "Helvetica"),
                   plot.title = element_text(size = consistent_font_size + 2, family = "Helvetica", face = "bold"),
                   axis.text = element_text(size = consistent_font_size - 2, family = "Helvetica")

            theme(

              text = element_text(family = "Helvetica"),

              axis.title.y = element_text(size = consistent_font_size, family = "Helvetica"),
              legend.title = element_text(size = consistent_font_size, family = "Helvetica"),
              legend.text = element_text(size = consistent_font_size - 2, family = "Helvetica"),
```

## Limitations
```{r}
#| echo: false
knitr::asis_output("* The Status variable over-represents living individuals, potentially skewing the results.
* The dataset, collected from 2006â2010, may not reflect current clinical practices, limiting the report's applicability.
* Absence of data on lymph node location constrains clinical interpretation.

Potential improvements include using recent cohort data and incorporating anatomical mapping of lymph node involvement, as recommended to enable spatial analysis of regional metastases.")
```
